XXI. It is to be observed, however, that there are some things which approach to the nature of usury, ancl commonly are held to be usury, which are pacts of another kind: as pacts for making good the loss which he suffers who lends money, by being kept out of his money so long: and on account of the gain which the money-leudei- loses by lending, deducting what corresponds to the uncertainty of his hopes, and the labour he would have had to undergo.
